Prateek KumarPrateek Kumar • 1st1st Scientist | Rational Thinker | Vegetarian by Choice | Atheist by Reason | Chess & Music Enthusiast | Debunking Pseudoscience with EvidenceScientist | Rational Thinker | Vegetarian by Choice | Atheist by Reason | Chess & Music Enthusiast | Debunking Pseudoscience with Evidence 1w • 1 week ago • Visible to anyone on or off LinkedIn
Today is the 147th birth anniversary of E.V. Ramasamy Periyar..!!

Periyar E.V. Ramasamy (1879–1973), often called Thanthai Periyar, was one of the most radical social reformers of modern India. His reforms, especially under the Self-Respect Movement, were deeply tied to the principles of rationality, atheism, and feminism :

1. Rationality

Critique of religion and superstition:
Periyar emphasized that society must be guided by reason rather than blind faith. He urged people to question rituals, caste customs, and myths, exposing them as tools of oppression.

Promotion of scientific thinking:
He encouraged the use of logic and empirical evidence in daily life, opposing astrology, priestly authority, and irrational practices.

Self-Respect Movement:
Founded in 1925, it stressed that a person’s worth should come from education, dignity, and rational conduct, not caste or inherited religion.

2. Atheism

Rejection of God:
Periyar was a staunch atheist, declaring that belief in God was a means by which Brahmins and upper castes maintained social control.

Temple-entry movement:
He fought against caste-based restrictions in temples but also questioned why temples were necessary at all.

‘No God, No Religion’ philosophy:
He argued that liberation of the oppressed could only come by dismantling the power of organized religion, which perpetuated caste hierarchies and gender inequality.

3. Feminism

Women’s liberation:
Periyar was far ahead of his time in demanding equality for women. He advocated for women’s education, property rights, and participation in politics.

Criticism of patriarchy:
He opposed child marriage, dowry, and the notion that women’s role was only to serve men.

Freedom in marriage and sexuality:
Periyar promoted widow remarriage, inter-caste marriages, and even advocated for women’s right to divorce—ideas considered revolutionary in his era.

Women as equals in Self-Respect Movement:
He ensured women actively participated in public life and protests, breaking the stereotype of submissive womanhood.

In short, Periyar’s reforms linked rationality, atheism, and feminism into one framework: dismantling oppressive traditions (caste, religion, patriarchy) and building a society based on equality, reason, and self-respect.

On his birth anniversary, let’s reflect on his radical courage and commitment to building a society where reason triumphs over superstition, equality over hierarchy, and dignity over discrimination.

Periyar’s ideas are not just history, they remain a guiding light for those who believe in social justice and rational humanism.

1w
To discredit him, some people have spread myth and false propaganda about him that he married his own daughter. Here are the facts :

Periyar married twice. His first wife was Nagammai, whom he married in 1898. She supported him in his early social reform activities and passed away in 1933.

In 1948, at the age of 70, Periyar married Maniammai (also called Maniammai), who was about 31 then.

Maniammai was not his daughter. She was a political disciple and active member of the Self-Respect Movement. She later became the leader of the Dravidar Kazhagam after Periyar’s death.

The marriage was controversial due to the large age gap, and his opponents spread the rumor that she was like his “adopted daughter.”

This was done to attack his personal life and weaken his movement.

In reality, Periyar himself openly declared his reasons: he wanted to ensure the continuity of his movement, and marrying Maniammai would give her the legal standing to inherit his property and carry forward the cause.

So, the claim that he married his “own daughter” is completely false. It was a smear campaign, not a fact.
